const web3: CategoryData = {
  ...getCategoryMeta("Web3")!,
  tracks: [{
    id: "web3-core", title: "Web3 Fundamentals", description: "Build decentralized applications with Web3 technologies.",
    modules: [
      {
        id: "web3-intro", title: "Web3 Architecture Overview",
        summary: "Web3 represents the third generation of the internet — a decentralized web built on blockchain technology that fundamentally changes how value transfers, data ownership, and digital identity work. Web1 was read-only (static HTML pages, consuming information), Web2 was read-write (social media, user-generated content, but controlled by centralized platforms), and Web3 is read-write-own — users control their data, digital identity, and assets through cryptographic keys. The core principles include decentralization (no single point of control or failure), permissionlessness (anyone can participate without gatekeepers), trustlessness (verifiable, automated rules instead of reliance on intermediaries), and self-sovereignty (users own their digital existence). Web3 applications (dApps) connect to blockchain networks through wallets like MetaMask and WalletConnect, which manage private keys locally and sign transactions that are broadcast to the network." +
    "The Web3 technology stack consists of multiple interdependent layers. At the base are Layer 1 blockchains like Ethereum (the dominant smart contract platform), Solana, and Polygon — each providing consensus, security, and settlement. On top of L1s run Layer 2 scaling solutions like Arbitrum, Optimism, and zkSync, which execute transactions off-chain or via validity proofs and post compressed data back to L1. Smart contracts — immutable programs deployed on the blockchain — define the application logic, from token transfers to complex DeFi protocols. Frontend frameworks (ethers.js, wagmi, web3.js) connect user interfaces to the blockchain by reading contract state and submitting signed transactions. Indexing protocols like The Graph make blockchain data queryable through GraphQL APIs, eliminating the need to scan the entire chain for relevant events." +
    "Off-chain infrastructure is equally critical. Oracle networks like Chainlink bring external data (asset prices, weather data, randomness) onto the blockchain in a cryptographically verifiable way. Decentralized storage systems (IPFS for content-addressed file storage, Arweave for permanent data archiving) host dApp frontends and NFT metadata without central servers. Identity protocols like ENS (Ethereum Name Service) map human-readable names to addresses, while Ceramic and Verifiable Credentials enable portable, self-sovereign identity. Messaging protocols like Waku and XMTP enable decentralized communication between users and dApps. The stack is modular — developers choose and compose these building blocks to create applications that no single entity controls, with censorship resistance and user ownership as the default properties." +
        "Web3's architecture introduces both opportunities and challenges compared to Web2. The decentralized nature means there is no central operator to appeal to if something goes wrong — lost keys mean lost access forever, and smart contract bugs can be exploited with no undo button. User experience suffers from the requirement of managing private keys, paying gas fees, and waiting for block confirmations. However, the benefits are transformative: users can take their identity and assets across applications (portability), developers can compose with any other protocol without asking permission (composability), and applications cannot be arbitrarily shut down or censored (resilience). Understanding this trade-off landscape is essential for anyone building or using Web3 applications.",
        essayQuestions: [
          { id: "web3-intro-q1", points: 20, question: "Your company wants to migrate from a Web2 SaaS model to a Web3 decentralized application. The product is a social media platform where users create content, follow creators, and receive recommendations. Write a detailed migration analysis comparing Web2 vs Web3 architecture for each component: user authentication (email/password vs wallet + SIWE), data storage (cloud databases vs IPFS/Ceramic), content moderation (centralized team vs DAO-driven + on-chain voting), monetization (subscription fees vs token-based microtransactions), and recommendation algorithms (server-side ML vs on-chain computation oracles). Identify which components benefit most from decentralization and where a hybrid Web2+Web3 approach might be appropriate." },
          { id: "web3-intro-q2", points: 20, question: "Your startup is choosing between building on Ethereum L1, an L2 rollup (Arbitrum/Optimism), or an alternative L1 (Solana/Polygon). Your application is a high-frequency trading bot that executes 1000+ transactions per day with sub-second latency requirements. Write a comparison analysis covering: block time and finality, transaction costs at varying network congestion levels, security assumptions (inheriting Ethereum security vs independent validator sets), developer tooling maturity, and liquidity/forking risk. Include concrete cost estimates for each option at 100, 1000, and 10,000 transactions per day." },
          { id: "web3-intro-q3", points: 20, question: "You're designing a decentralized file storage dApp that lets users upload, share, and permanently store files. Design the full architecture: which storage layers do you use for different data types (profile pictures vs large documents vs metadata), how do you ensure content availability (pinning, redundancy, incentives), how do you handle file versioning and deletion, what privacy guarantees can you offer (public vs encrypted vs access-controlled), and what economic model sustains the storage (one-time payment, recurring fees, token staking)? Include the smart contract interfaces and the IPFS/Arweave integration points." },
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "web3-stack", title: "The Web3 Technology Stack",
        summary: "The Web3 technology stack is a multi-layered software architecture where each layer solves a specific infrastructure challenge. Layer 1 blockchains like Ethereum form the foundation — they provide distributed consensus (ordering and finalizing transactions), security (economic incentives that make attacks prohibitively expensive), and a global state machine (the EVM). Consensus mechanisms have evolved from Proof of Work (Bitcoin, Ethereum pre-Merge) to Proof of Stake (Ethereum post-Merge, Solana, Polygon), dramatically reducing energy consumption. Each L1 makes different trade-offs along the blockchain trilemma of security, scalability, and decentralization — Ethereum prioritizes security and decentralization, while Solana prioritizes scalability with higher hardware requirements." +
    "Layer 2 scaling solutions address L1 throughput limitations by handling execution off-chain while anchoring security to L1. Optimistic rollups (Arbitrum, Optimism) assume transactions are valid unless challenged during a 7-day fraud proof window. ZK-rollups (zkSync, StarkNet, Scroll) generate validity proofs that are verified on L1, providing instant finality. Validiums (Immutable X) use off-chain data availability for even lower costs but weaker security guarantees. Sidechains (Polygon PoS) maintain independent validator sets with their own security models. Each scaling approach makes different trade-offs between cost, latency, security, and developer experience — ZK-rollups offer the best security but are harder to develop for, while optimistic rollups are more EVM-compatible but have withdrawal delays." +
    "Middleware protocols bridge the gap between raw blockchain data and usable application interfaces. The Graph indexes blockchain events and exposes them as GraphQL endpoints — a dApp queries The Graph instead of scanning the chain directly, reducing latency and complexity. IPFS (InterPlanetary File System) provides content-addressed storage where files are identified by their cryptographic hash rather than a server URL, enabling verifiable, decentralized hosting. Chainlink runs a decentralized oracle network where node operators stake LINK tokens to secure data feeds — if they provide incorrect data, their stake is slashed. These middleware protocols form a decentralized infrastructure layer that replaces AWS, Google Cloud, and centralized APIs in the Web2 stack." +
        "The stack also includes identity and connectivity layers. Wallets (MetaMask as browser extension, WalletConnect as mobile bridge, Rainbow as mobile-first UX) manage key pairs and provide a consistent interface across dApps. Account Abstraction (ERC-4337) replaces EOA-based accounts with smart contract wallets that support custom validation logic — social recovery, multi-sig, session keys, gas sponsorship. Identity protocols like ENS, Lens Protocol, and Ceramic create portable, user-owned identity graphs that span applications. Developer tooling (Hardhat for testing, Foundry for fast compilation, Wagmi for React hooks, Viem for TypeScript-first libraries) has matured significantly, making Web3 development more accessible while retaining its unique architectural principles.",
        essayQuestions: [
          { id: "web3-stack-q1", points: 20, question: "Your organization is building a cross-chain NFT bridge that lets users mint NFTs on Ethereum and transfer them to Polygon and Arbitrum. Design the bridge architecture: how do you lock/burn NFTs on the source chain, mint/release on the destination, and verify the transfer on both sides? Compare three approaches: (1) a multi-sig validator set, (2) an optimistic bridge with fraud proofs, (3) a ZK bridge with validity proofs. For each approach, analyze security (validator collusion risk, finality delays), cost (L1 gas for verification, L2 transaction fees), and latency (time from initiation to completion)." },
          { id: "web3-stack-q2", points: 20, question: "Your dApp is suffering from high latency because your frontend queries Ethereum directly for every data read. Redesign the data flow using The Graph for historical queries, a local cache for frequently accessed data, and direct RPC calls only when fresh state is needed. Include the GraphQL schemas for your subgraph, the caching strategy (TTL, invalidation on chain events), and the fallback logic when The Graph is unavailable. Also describe how you'd handle real-time updates using WebSocket subscriptions." },
          { id: "web3-stack-q3", points: 20, question: "Your DeFi protocol relies on Chainlink price oracles for 8 different asset pairs. During a flash crash, one oracle reports a stale price that causes cascading liquidations. Write a oracle risk analysis: how does Chainlink's decentralized oracle network work (node selection, aggregation, staking), what happens during network congestion (delay in price updates), and how do you protect against stale price feeds? Design a multi-oracle strategy with Circuit Breaker logic that compares Chainlink data against a secondary TWAP oracle and pauses liquidations if deviation exceeds 2%." },
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "web3-wallets", title: "Wallet Integration & UX",
        summary: "Web3 wallets are the gateway to decentralized applications — they manage cryptographic key pairs, sign transactions and messages, connect to dApps through standardized protocols, and provide users with a consistent interface for managing their on-chain identity and assets. The user experience of wallet interaction is arguably the most important factor in Web3 adoption. The two fundamental account types are Externally Owned Accounts (EOAs) — controlled by a private key held by the user — and smart contract wallets (also called account abstraction wallets) — controlled by code with programmable validation logic. EOAs are simpler and more widely supported but limited in functionality: a lost key means lost funds, there's no multi-sig or recovery, and every transaction requires the user's direct signature." +
    "Wallet connection protocols have standardized through EIP-1193 (the Ethereum provider API) and WalletConnect (a bridge protocol that enables mobile wallet to dApp connections without browser extensions). The window.ethereum provider injected by MetaMask and other browser extensions exposes a JSON-RPC interface for account access, signing, and transaction submission. WalletConnect V2 uses a relay server to establish encrypted connections between a dApp (running in a browser or desktop app) and a mobile wallet via QR code scan. EIP-6963 (Multi-Injected Provider Discovery) solves the problem of multiple wallet extensions competing for the window.ethereum provider. Modern dApps use libraries like Web3Modal (by WalletConnect) or RainbowKit that present a standardized wallet selection UI supporting dozens of wallets." +
    "Smart contract wallets are transforming the wallet UX paradigm. Safe (formerly Gnosis Safe) pioneered multi-sig wallets requiring M-of-N signatures for transactions — essential for DAO treasuries and protocol operations. Argent popularized social recovery: guardians (trusted friends, hardware wallets, or institutional custodians) can collectively authorize a wallet migration if the owner loses access. ERC-4337 introduced account abstraction natively at the protocol level: UserOperations (bundled by bundlers) replace regular transactions, EntryPoint contracts validate signatures off-chain, and paymasters can sponsor gas fees. This enables session keys (sign once for many transactions), batch transactions (approve + swap + deposit in one click), and gasless/fees-in-ERC-20 experiences." +
        "The UX challenges of wallets remain a significant adoption barrier. Seed phrase management (12 or 24 words) is error-prone — users write them down incorrectly, store them insecurely, or lose them entirely. Transaction confirmation requires users to understand gas fees, nonces, chain IDs, and approval amounts — concepts that don't exist in Web2. dApps must provide clear transaction previews showing exactly what will happen (which tokens, which amounts, which protocols), network switching prompts when the user is on the wrong chain, and human-readable explanations of what each contract interaction does. EIP-4361 (Sign-In with Ethereum) provides a standardized way for dApps to authenticate users via signed messages, replacing username/password with a cryptographic proof of address ownership. The wallet UX is the make-or-break factor for Web3 mass adoption — improving it is as important as any scalability or security innovation.",
        essayQuestions: [
          { id: "web3-wallets-q1", points: 20, question: "Your dApp has been running for 2 years with basic MetaMask EOA wallet support. You now need to support smart contract wallets (Safe, Argent) and cross-chain transactions. Write a wallet integration upgrade plan: implement WalletConnect V2 for mobile support, use Web3Modal/RainbowKit for multi-wallet connection UI, handle EIP-1193 provider events (accountsChanged, chainChanged, disconnect), detect and warn users when they're on the wrong network, and implement EIP-4361 Sign-In with Ethereum for session authentication. Include the specific wagmi/viem hooks and the SIWE message format." },
          { id: "web3-wallets-q2", points: 20, question: "Your token swap dApp is getting customer support tickets from users who accidentally sent tokens to the wrong address, signed malicious approve() transactions, or lost their seed phrase. Write a wallet safety and UX analysis covering: (1) what information to show users before each transaction (token approval amounts vs limits, recipient address verification, estimated gas), (2) how to simulate transactions before sending them (eth_call with the user's address, checking for reverts), (3) warning indicators for suspicious interactions (unlimited approvals, contract interactions with unverified source code, transfers to blacklisted addresses), and (4) recovery options if something goes wrong." },
          { id: "web3-wallets-q3", points: 20, question: "Your protocol wants to implement 'gasless' transactions where you sponsor the gas costs for your users. Design a paymaster infrastructure using ERC-4337 account abstraction. Explain: how the UserOperation flow works (wallet creates op, bundler submits to EntryPoint, paymaster verifies conditions, EntryPoint executes), how your paymaster validates sponsorship conditions (only for your protocol's contract calls, only up to a daily limit per user, only if the user has sufficient token balance to reimburse you), and how you handle the economic risk (users who never reimburse you, token price fluctuations, spam attacks). Include Solidity code for the paymaster contract." },
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "web3-building", title: "Building dApps",
        summary: "Building a production-grade decentralized application requires mastery of the entire development lifecycle: smart contract development, testing, deployment, frontend integration, and ongoing operations. The most popular development frameworks are Hardhat (JavaScript/TypeScript, extensible with plugins, excellent debugging) and Foundry (Rust-based, extremely fast compilation and testing, Solidity-native). The standard workflow begins with contract architecture design (identifying which logic belongs on-chain vs off-chain, defining storage layouts, designing upgrade strategies), followed by implementation in Solidity. The Solidity compiler (solc) versions have evolved rapidly — modern Solidity 0.8.x includes built-in overflow checks, custom errors, ABI encoder v2, and more expressive type system features." +
    "Testing is arguably the most important phase in dApp development, given the immutable nature of deployed contracts. Unit tests verify individual function behavior under normal conditions and edge cases. Integration tests verify interactions between contracts (a lending protocol's deposit affects available liquidity). Fork tests clone mainnet state to test against real deployed protocols (testing a DEX swap against the actual Uniswap pools). Fuzz testing (Foundry's ffi, Echidna) generates random inputs to discover edge cases. Invariant testing asserts that certain properties always hold (totalSupply always equals sum of balances, a lending protocol is always overcollateralized). The testing pyramid for smart contracts is deeper than traditional software — the financial consequences of bugs demand much higher coverage and more sophisticated testing strategies." +
    "Frontend integration connects users to smart contracts. The ethers.js library provides a complete Ethereum interaction toolkit: Contract objects that mirror the Solidity ABI, Signers that represent user wallets, Providers that connect to the network, and utilities for formatting ether, encoding function calls, and parsing events. Modern React dApps typically use wagmi (a collection of composable React hooks for account, contract, balance, and signature interactions) combined with Viem (a TypeScript-first, tree-shakeable replacement for ethers.js that is smaller, faster, and type-safe). The frontend architecture usually follows a predictable pattern: a wallet connection flow, read calls to display contract state, write calls that trigger transactions, and event listeners that update the UI when state changes." +
        "Deployment and operations close the development cycle. Contracts are first deployed to testnets (Sepolia, Holesky for Ethereum; Arbitrum Sepolia, OP Sepolia for L2s) where they can be tested with test ETH and real third-party integrations. Mainnet deployment is a multi-phase process typically managed through a multi-sig with timelock: deploy implementation, deploy proxy, initialize storage, verify on Etherscan, set up monitoring (Tenderly, Defender), and gradually increase TVL. Production monitoring tracks contract interactions, gas costs, error rates, and suspicious activity. Bug bounties (Immunefi is the most popular platform) incentivize security researchers to find vulnerabilities before attackers do. Regular security reviews (quarterly audits, continuous formal verification) maintain security as the codebase evolves with upgrades.",
        essayQuestions: [
          { id: "web3-building-q1", points: 20, question: "Your team is building a DeFi lending protocol and must choose between Foundry and Hardhat as the development framework. Write a comparison analysis evaluating: compilation speed, testing (fuzz testing, invariant testing, fork testing), debugging (console.log in Solidity, stack traces), deployment scripts, TypeScript integration, plugin ecosystem, and gas profiling. Your protocol has 12 interconnected contracts and needs sophisticated fork testing against mainnet Aave, Uniswap, and Compound. Which framework do you recommend and what specific workflow would you establish for your team?" },
          { id: "web3-building-q2", points: 20, question: "Your NFT marketplace contract has a critical bug: the buy() function doesn't check if the NFT is still listed before processing the payment. During a code review, you identify this as a reentrancy vulnerability. Write the test suite that would catch this bug: a Foundry fuzz test generating random order states (listed, cancelled, sold), a fork test simulating the actual attack scenario (reentrant call from a malicious buyer contract), and an invariant test asserting that a buyer cannot purchase an NFT that is not currently listed. Then implement the fix using the Checks-Effects-Interactions pattern and configure a reentrancy guard." },
          { id: "web3-building-q3", points: 20, question: "Your React dApp processes 500,000 NFT metadata queries per day but is slow because each query makes an RPC call to the blockchain. Redesign the data fetching architecture: implement a wagmi/React-Query based caching layer, use The Graph subgraph for historical data and batch queries, use a local cache (Redis or IndexedDB) for frequently accessed metadata, and set up WebSocket subscriptions for real-time updates (new mints, price changes). How do you handle cache invalidation when new blocks are mined? How does the dApp gracefully degrade when The Graph is slow but the chain is available?" },
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-1", title: "Web3 Architecture & dApp Development",
        summary: "Building a comprehensive Web3 application requires understanding the full architecture stack from blockchain fundamentals to user interface patterns. The Web3 architecture differs fundamentally from Web2 — instead of a client-server model where a central database stores user data and a central server processes requests, Web3 applications use a distributed network of nodes running the same deterministic state machine (the EVM), with user wallets acting as both identity provider and signing device. Data is stored across multiple layers: on-chain for critical state (balances, ownership, protocol parameters), IPFS for content-addressed files (NFT metadata, frontend assets), and Arweave for permanent archival. The application logic is split between on-chain smart contracts (immutable, transparent, composable) and off-chain indexers and aggregators (performant, flexible, cheaper)." +
    "dApp development requires orchestrating multiple infrastructure components simultaneously. The smart contract layer defines the protocol's core logic — token transfers, lending pools, swap mechanics, governance voting. These contracts are composed like lego bricks: a lending protocol integrates with a price oracle, a flash loan provider, and a liquidation bot. The indexing layer (The Graph subgraphs) transforms raw blockchain events into structured, queryable data — instead of scanning the entire chain history for a user's transactions, a dApp queries its subgraph for that user's event history in milliseconds. The frontend layer handles wallet connection (via ethers.js, wagmi, or Web3Modal), reads data from either the chain (for fresh state) or The Graph (for historical data), and submits user-authorized transactions through the wallet." +
    "Composability is Web3's superpower. A single transaction can atomically compose multiple protocols: borrow from Aave using deposited USDC as collateral, swap the borrowed ETH for DAI on Uniswap, deposit DAI into a Yearn vault, and stake the resulting yvDAI tokens on Convex — all in one atomic transaction. This 'money lego' composability creates entirely new financial primitives that are impossible in traditional finance. However, it also introduces systemic risk — a vulnerability in one protocol can cascade across the entire ecosystem. The 2022-2023 exploit wave (Ronin, Wormhole, Euler, Curve) all exploited composability chains where a single entry point led to protocol-wide compromise. Defensive composability requires careful integration checks, circuit breakers, and independent audits of each integration path." +
        "The developer experience continues to improve rapidly. Hardhat's console.log debugging, Foundry's fuzz testing, and Tenderly's transaction simulation make development more approachable. New frameworks like Scaffold-ETH provide complete starter kits with pre-configured smart contracts, frontend boilerplate, and deployment scripts. The Graph's hosted service simplifies subgraph deployment. Testnet faucets, chain explorers, and wallet developer tools have matured. Despite these improvements, Web3 development remains more complex than Web2 — developers must understand gas optimization, storage layout management, upgradeability patterns, and economic security. The principle of 'trust but verify' applies to every integration and dependency.",
        essayQuestions: [
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-1-q1", points: 20, question: "Your team is designing a decentralized content platform where creators publish articles, readers tip in ETH/DAI, and the platform has zero control over content moderation (no takedown mechanism). Design the full architecture: how are articles stored (on-chain vs IPFS vs Arweave), how does the tipping mechanism work (direct wallet-to-wallet vs via a smart contract escrow), how are creator identities verified (ENS + on-chain attestations), how is content discovery and search implemented (The Graph indexing), and how does the platform handle illegal/spam content if there's no central moderator? Address the tension between censorship resistance and legal compliance." },
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-1-q2", points: 20, question: "Your DeFi protocol needs to support cross-chain money markets where users deposit on Ethereum and borrow on Arbitrum. Design the cross-chain architecture: how does the bridge verify the deposit on Ethereum before allowing the borrow on Arbitrum (optimistic vs ZK vs multi-sig), how are interest rates synchronized across chains, what happens if the bridge goes down (can users still withdraw on the source chain), and how do liquidations work when positions are cross-chain? Include the smart contract interfaces and the economic security model for the bridge." },
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-1-q3", points: 20, question: "Your gas optimization study reveals that your dApp's most expensive operation is reading user positions from storage during the liquidation process. Design a gas optimization strategy: use struct packing for user position data, implement a caching layer for frequently accessed storage slots, batch multiple user updates into a single transaction, and use merkle trees for off-chain position verification. Show the before/after gas costs for each optimization and explain the security implications of each change." },
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-2", title: "Web3 Security & Best Practices",
        summary: "Web3 application security extends far beyond smart contract auditing - it encompasses the entire stack from wallet integration to backend infrastructure to user education. At the wallet and authentication layer, the biggest risks are phishing (fake dApps that trick users into signing malicious transactions), clipboard hijacking (replacing copied addresses), and seed phrase theft (via fake wallet apps, browser extensions, or social engineering). Users must be educated about verifying transaction details before signing, using hardware wallets for significant holdings, and never entering seed phrases into any website. dApp developers must implement clear transaction previews, verify network IDs before submitting transactions, and never store private keys client-side. The Web3 security model shifts responsibility from platform operators to users - a paradigm that requires fundamentally different UX patterns for security." +
        "Smart contract vulnerabilities remain the most catastrophic risk class. Beyond reentrancy and oracle manipulation, modern exploits often combine multiple vulnerabilities across different protocols in a single atomic transaction using flash loans for capital. The Euler Finance exploit ($197M), the Curve pools exploit ($73M), and the Mango Markets exploit ($114M) all demonstrated how sophisticated attackers combine flash loans, oracle manipulation, and protocol-specific logic flaws. Defending against these requires defense-in-depth: multiple independent oracles with deviation checks, circuit breakers that pause abnormal activity, rate limiting on withdrawal sizes, and economic measures like deposit caps and liquidation bonuses that make attacks unprofitable. Formal verification of critical invariants provides mathematical guarantees that complement manual auditing." +
        "Infrastructure security covers RPC endpoints, IPFS hosting, and indexing services. Shared RPC providers (Alchemy, Infura) are single points of failure - if they rate-limit or censor your dApp, users can't interact with the contracts. Solutions include running your own node, using multiple RPC providers with failover, or using decentralized RPC networks (Pocket Network, Lit Protocol). IPFS hosting raises concerns about content availability - if the pinning service goes down, NFT images break and dApp frontends become inaccessible. Redundant pinning across multiple services, alongside Arweave permanent storage backups, mitigates this risk. DNS attacks on IPFS gateways or ENS domain hijacking can redirect users to malicious dApp versions. DNSSEC, ENS locking, and immutable IPFS hashes provide protection." +
        "Operational security covers the deployment and upgrade process. Private keys for deployment accounts, multi-sig signers, and admin roles must be stored securely - hardware wallets in bank safety deposit boxes, with geographic distribution of signers for critical protocols. Upgrade processes should follow a formal protocol: design document, implementation, internal review, professional audit, staging deployment, timelock activation, mainnet deployment with monitoring. The DAO hack aftermath taught the industry about governance attacks where an attacker accumulates enough voting power to pass malicious treasury-draining proposals. Mitigations include timelocks, proposal deposits, quorum requirements, whale voting caps, and emergency veto mechanisms held by trusted guardians. Web3 security is ultimately about managing risk across a distributed, adversarial, and rapidly evolving landscape.",
        essayQuestions: [
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-2-q1", points: 20, question: "Your dApp has 500,000 monthly active users, and phishing attacks are the #1 support ticket. Users are connecting to fake versions of your dApp hosted on lookalike domains and signing drainer transactions. Design a comprehensive anti-phishing strategy covering: (1) technical measures (DNS hardening, IPFS hash verification in-wallet, EIP-4361 Sign-In with Ethereum for session verification), (2) user education (what to show users during wallet connection), (3) monitoring (detecting fake domains and getting them taken down), and (4) recovery (how to help victims after an attack). Write the specific UI components and warning messages you'd implement." },
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-2-q2", points: 20, question: "Your lending protocol uses a TWAP oracle from Uniswap V3 with a 30-minute window. An attacker uses a flash loan to manipulate the spot price on Uniswap for one block, then exploits a front-run opportunity before the TWAP smooths out. Write a security analysis of TWAP oracle limitations: what are the minimum manipulation costs for a given pool depth and TWAP window? How do you choose the optimal TWAP window that balances freshness vs manipulation resistance? Also propose additional defenses: a price deviation circuit breaker that pauses if the oracle price deviates more than X% from a secondary oracle, and a minimum liquidity requirement for using a pool as an oracle source." },
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-2-q3", points: 20, question: "Your protocol's multi-sig signers use Ledger hardware wallets, but three of nine signers lost their devices during a house fire. The recovery seed phrases were stored in bank safe deposit boxes in three different cities. The protocol is frozen because treasury transactions require 5-of-9 signatures. Design a key recovery and governance continuity plan: how can the remaining signers regain control? Should you have used a lower threshold or a social recovery mechanism? How does the Safe contract's threshold change mechanism work? What operational procedures should be put in place to prevent this in the future?" },
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-3", title: "Web3 Production Deployment",
        summary: "Deploying a Web3 application to production is a multi-phase process that requires meticulous planning, coordination, and verification at every step. Unlike traditional web deployments where you can push a bug fix and redeploy instantly, blockchain deployments are permanent - every deployed contract bytecode is immutable, and every bug is a potential exploit. The production deployment pipeline begins with contract development and testing, proceeds through audit and formal verification, then deploys via a carefully orchestrated multi-sig process. Each environment (local, testnet, mainnet) has different security requirements and operational procedures. The deployment process should be scripted, versioned, and executed by a multi-sig with a timelock to allow for last-minute cancellation if issues are detected." +
        "The pre-deployment phase focuses on verification and security. After development and unit testing, contracts undergo professional audit by 2-3 independent firms. Audit scope includes the threat model, attack surface analysis, economic security, and edge case analysis. Critical findings are fixed and re-audited. Formal verification using tools like Certora or Scribble mathematically proves key invariants. Fuzz testing with Foundry generates thousands of random inputs to find edge cases. Gas profiling ensures the contract is economically viable. Testnet deployment mirrors the mainnet deployment process - deploy, verify on Etherscan, test with realistic conditions (multiple users, third-party integrations, network congestion)." +
        "The mainnet deployment itself is a high-stakes operation typically executed by a multi-sig with a timelock. The deployment script executes each step sequentially and verifies each one before proceeding: deploy implementation contracts, deploy proxy contracts, initialize storage (with the correct parameters - timelock duration, multi-sig addresses, oracle addresses, fee parameters), verify all source code on Etherscan, set up monitoring and alerts, and finally transfer ownership of the proxy admin to the multi-sig. Each step is a separate multi-sig transaction to allow independent verification. The initial TVL is typically capped to limit risk exposure. Gradual parameter adjustments over the first weeks are executed through governance with timelocks." +
        "Post-deployment operations are as critical as the deployment itself. Monitoring infrastructure tracks on-chain metrics (TVL, user count, transaction volume, failed transactions) and off-chain metrics (frontend availability, API latency, error rates). Automated alerts notify the team of unusual activity - large price deviations across oracles, unusual volume spikes, failed multi-sig transaction attempts. Incident response procedures define how the team handles emergencies: circuit breaker activation, oracle fallback switching, pause protocol, and post-mortem analysis. Regular security reviews (quarterly audits, continuous bug bounty, periodic formal verification) maintain security over time. The operational team must be on-call 24/7, with clear escalation procedures and the authority to trigger emergency pauses. Web3 production operations require a level of rigor closer to aerospace or nuclear engineering than traditional web development.",
        essayQuestions: [
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-3-q1", points: 20, question: "Your protocol is deploying to mainnet tomorrow. The deployment requires 9 sequential transactions across 4 contracts. Any mistake could compromise the protocol or lock user funds. Write the complete deployment playbook: step-by-step instructions for each transaction, the specific multi-sig signers required, verification steps between each transaction (check contract code on Etherscan, verify storage slots, test initialization), rollback procedures if a step fails, and the emergency contacts to call if something unexpected happens. Include the exact safe transaction builder calls for Gnosis Safe." },
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-3-q2", points: 20, question: "Your lending protocol was deployed with a timelock of 48 hours. During a market crash, the protocol needs to adjust liquidation thresholds urgently to prevent cascading liquidations, but the timelock prevents any change for 48 hours. Write a post-mortem analysis of this scenario: should you have used a shorter timelock for risk parameters? Should there be a guardian role that can bypass the timelock for emergency parameter changes? What attack does the timelock prevent vs what risk does it create? Design a multi-tier governance architecture with: (1) emergency guardian (2/3 multi-sig, 1 hour delay for pause-only), (2) risk parameter adjustment (3/5 multi-sig, 24 hour delay), and (3) full upgrade (5/7 multi-sig, 7 day delay)." },
          { id: "web3-fundamentals-essay-3-q3", points: 20, question: "Your protocol was deployed 6 months ago and now needs an upgrade to fix a critical bug. The upgrade requires changing the storage layout - you need to add two new state variables. Write an upgrade impact analysis: how the new variables affect existing storage slots, whether the existing proxy storage is compatible, and what happens to existing user data after the upgrade. Implement the UUPS upgrade: deploy the new implementation, verify the storage layout is compatible using the OpenZeppelin storage gap pattern, test the upgrade on a mainnet fork, and execute the upgrade through governance. Include the Solidity storage layout verification code." },
        ]
      },
    ]
  }]
};

